11 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
12 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 36 O.S. 2021, Section 985, is
13 amended to read as follows:
14 Section 985. Ratemaking Standards.
15 A. A rate may not be excessive, inadequate or unfairly
16 discriminatory.
17 1. No rate in a competitive market may be determined to be
18 excessive. A rate in a noncompetitive market may be determined to
19 be excessive if it, based on actuarial review, the rate is likely to
20 produce a profit that is unreasonably high for the insurance
21 provided. The Insurance Commissioner shall send an objection to the
22 insurer and shall give the insurer the opportunity to respond and
23 provide additional supporting information prior to making a final
24 determination that the rate is excessive.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3781 Page 2

1 2. A rate may not be determined to be inadequate unless:
2 a. the rate is clearly insufficient to sustain projected
3 losses, expenses and special assessments, and
4 b. the rate is unreasonably low and use of the rate by
5 the insurer has tended or, if continued, will tend to
6 create a monopoly in the market.
7 3. Unfair discrimination may be determined to exist if, after
8 allowing for practical limitations, price differentials fail to
9 reflect equitably the differences in expected losses and expenses.
10 A rate may not be determined to be unfairly discriminatory because
11 different premiums result for policyholders with like loss exposures
12 but different expense levels, or like expenses but different loss
13 exposures, or if it averaged broadly among persons insured within a
14 group, franchise or blanket policy or a mass-marketed plan. No rate
15 in a competitive market shall be considered unfairly discriminatory
16 unless it classifies risk on the basis of race, color, creed, or
17 national origin, or religion.
18 B. In determining whether rates in a noncompetitive market are
19 excessive, inadequate, or unfairly discriminatory, due consideration
20 may be given to:
21 1. Past and prospective loss experience within and outside this
22 state, in accordance with accepted actuarial principles;
23 2. Conflagration and catastrophe hazards;
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3781 Page 3

1 3. A reasonable margin for underwriting profit and
2 contingencies;
3 4. Loadings for leveling premium rates over time for dividends,
4 savings or unabsorbed premium deposits allowed or returned by
5 insurers to their policyholders, members or subscribers;
6 5. Past and prospective expenses both countrywide and those
7 specially applicable to this state; and
8 6. Provisions for special assessments; and to all other
9 relevant factors including judgment within and outside this state.
10 C. Risks may be grouped by classifications for the
11 establishment of rates and minimum premiums. Classification rates
12 may be modified to produce rates for individual risks in accordance
13 with rating plans which establish standards for measuring variations
14 in hazards or expense provisions, or both. Such standards may
15 measure any differences among risks that can be demonstrated to have
16 a probable effect upon losses or expenses. No risk classification,
17 however, may be based on race, color, creed, national origin, or the
18 religion of the insured.
19 D. The expense provisions included in the rates for use by an
20 insurer or group of insurers may differ from those of any other
21 insurer or group of insurers to reflect the requirements of the
22 operating methods of the insurer or group of insurers.
23 E. The rates may contain provision for contingencies and an
24 allowance permitting a reasonable profit. In determining the
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3781 Page 4

1 reas onableness of the profit, consideration shall be given to the
2 investment income attributable to the line of insurance.
3 F. Risks may be classified in any way except that no risk may
4 be classified on the basis of race, color, creed, or national
5 origin, or religion of the insured.
6 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 36 O.S. 2021, Section 987, is
7 amended to read as follows:
8 Section 987. Rate Filings.
9 A. In a competitive market, every insurer shall file with the
10 Insurance Commissioner all rates and, supplementary rate information
11 to be used in this state no later than thirty (30) days after the
12 effective date; provided, that the rates and supplementary rate
13 information need not be filed for commercial risks, which by general
14 custom are not written according to manual rules or rating plans.
15 B. In a noncompetitive market, every insurer shall file with
16 the Commissioner all rates, supplementary rate information and
17 supporting information at least thirty (30) days before the proposed
18 effective date. The Commissioner may give written notice, within
19 thirty (30) days of receipt of the filing, that the Commissioner
20 needs additional time, not to exceed thirty (30) days from the date
21 of the notice to consider the filing. Upon written application of
22 the insurer, the Commissioner may authorize rates to be effective
23 before the expiration of the waiting period or an extension thereof.
24 A filing shall be deemed to meet the requirements of the Property
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 3781 Page 5

1 and Casualty Competitive Loss Cost Rating Act and to become
2 effective unless disapproved pursuant to this title by the
3 Commissioner before the expiration of the waiting period or an
4 extension thereof.
5 In a noncompetitive market, the filing shall be deemed in
6 compliance with the filing provision of this section unless the
7 Commissioner informs the insurer within ten (10) days after receipt
8 of the filings as to what supplementary rate information or
9 supporting information is required to complete the filing.
10 C. Every authorized insurer shall file with the Commissioner,
11 except as to rates for those lines of insurance exempted from the
12 provisions of the Property and Casualty Competitive Loss Cost Rating
13 Act by the Commissioner under subsections E and F of this section
14 and except for those risks designated as special risks under Section
15 997 of this title, all rates, supplementary rate information and any
16 changes and amendments which it proposes to use. An insurer may
17 file its rates by either filing its final rates or by filing a
18 multiplier and, if applicable, an expense constant adjustment to be
19 applied to prospective loss costs that have been filed by an
20 advisory organization as permitted by this title. Such loss cost
21 multiplier filing and expense constant filings made by insurers
